Given the root of a binary tree, return its maximum depth.

A binary tree's maximum depth is the number of nodes along the longest path from the root node down to the farthest leaf node.

Example 1:

Input: root = [3,9,20,null,null,15,7]
Output: 3

Soln:

The depth of any node is simply:
1 + {max}({depth of left child},{depth of right child})

Base Case: If a node is null, its depth is 0.
Recursive Step:Go down the Left side and find its depth. Go down the Right side and find its depth. Pick the larger of the two and add 1 (counting the current node itself).

BFS:

class Solution 
{
    public int maxDepth(TreeNode root) 
    {
        if(root==null)
        {
            return 0;
        }
        Queue <TreeNode> queue = new LinkedList<>();
        queue.offer(root);
        int depth = 0;

        while(!queue.isEmpty())
        {
            int levelsize = queue.size();  // 1. Snapshot the size! This tells us how many nodes are on THIS level.

            for(int i=0; i<levelsize; i++)     // 2. Process all nodes on this level
            {
                TreeNode current = queue.poll();

                if(current.left != null)
                {
                    queue.offer(current.left);
                }
                if(current.right != null)
                {
                    queue.offer(current.right);
                }
            }
            depth++;     // 3. We finished a level, so increment depth
        }
        return depth;
    }
}


DFS:
class Solution 
{
    public int maxDepth(TreeNode root) 
    {
        if(root==null)
        {
            return 0;
        }
        int leftDepth = maxDepth(root.left);
        int rightDepth = maxDepth(root.right);

        return Math.max(leftDepth, rightDepth) + 1;
    }
}
